def char_frequency(s):
    frequency = {}
    for char in s:
        if char in frequency:
            frequency[char] += 1
        else:
            frequency[char] = 1
    return frequency

# Example usage:
input_string = "hello world"
result = char_frequency(input_string)
print(result)
```

This function iterates through each character in the input string `s`. If a character is already a key in the dictionary `frequency`, it increments its value by one. Otherwise, it adds the character as a new key with an initial value of 1. This way, all unique characters and their frequencies are stored in the dictionary. The time complexity is O(n), where n is the length of the string, because each character must be examined once. The space complexity is also O(n) in the worst case when every character in the string is unique.

