def fib(n, memo=None):
    if memo is None:
        memo = {}
    if n in memo:
        return memo[n]
    if n == 0 or n == 1:
        memo[n] = n
    else:
        memo[n] = fib(n-1, memo) + fib(n-2, memo)
    return memo[n]

# Example usage:
print(fib(10))  # Output will be 55
```

This function uses a dictionary to store previously calculated Fibonlos numbers and avoids redundant calculations, significantly improving performance for larger inputs.

